javax.time.calendrical

Interface TemporalField

  • All Superinterfaces:
    Comparator<TemporalAccessor>
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    ChronoField, JulianDayField

    public interface TemporalField
extends Comparator<TemporalAccessor>
    A field of date or time, such as month-of-year or hour-of-minute.

    Date and time is expressed using fields which partition the time-line into something meaningful for humans. Implementations of this interface represent those fields.

    The most commonly used units are defined in ChronoField. Additional fields can be written by application code by implementing this interface.

    The field works using double dispatch. Client code calls methods on a date-time like LocalDateTime which check if the field is a ChronoField. If it is, then the date-time must handle it. Otherwise, the method call is re-dispatched to the matching method in this interface.

    Implementation notes

    This interface must be implemented with care to ensure other classes operate correctly. All implementations that can be instantiated must be final, immutable and thread-safe. It is recommended to use an enum where possible.

    • Method Detail

      • getName

        String getName()
        Gets a descriptive name for the field.

        The should be of the format 'BaseOfRange', such as 'MonthOfYear', unless the field is unbounded, such as 'Year' or 'Era', when only the base unit is mentioned.

        Returns:
        the name, not null

      • getBaseUnit

        TemporalUnit getBaseUnit()
        Gets the unit that the field is measured in.

        The unit of the field is the period that varies within the range. For example, in the field 'MonthOfYear', the unit is 'Months'. See also getRangeUnit().

        Returns:
        the period unit defining the base unit of the field, not null

      • getRangeUnit

        TemporalUnit getRangeUnit()
        Gets the range that the field is bound by.

        The range of the field is the period that the field varies within. For example, in the field 'MonthOfYear', the range is 'Years'. See also getBaseUnit().

        The range is never null. For example, the 'Year' field is shorthand for 'YearOfForever'. It therefore has a unit of 'Years' and a range of 'Forever'.

        Returns:
        the period unit defining the range of the field, not null

      • compare

        int compare(TemporalAccessor temporal1,
          TemporalAccessor temporal2)
        Compares the value of this field in two temporal objects.

        All fields implement Comparator on TemporalAccessor. This allows a list of temporal objects to be compared using the value of a field. For example, you could sort a list of arbitrary temporal objects by the value of the month-of-year field - Collections.sort(list, MONTH_OF_YEAR)

        This default implementation uses TemporalAccessor.getLong(TemporalField) to determine the values to compare.

        Specified by:
        compare in interface Comparator<TemporalAccessor>
        Parameters:
        temporal1 - the first temporal object to compare, not null
        temporal2 - the second temporal object to compare, not null
        Returns:
        a negative integer, zero, or a positive integer as the first argument is less than, equal to, or greater than the second.
        Throws:
        DateTimeException - if unable to obtain the value for this field

      • range

        TemporalValueRange range()
        Gets the range of valid values for the field.

        All fields can be expressed as a long integer. This method returns an object that describes the valid range for that value. This method is generally only applicable to the ISO-8601 calendar system.

        Note that the result only describes the minimum and maximum valid values and it is important not to read too much into them. For example, there could be values within the range that are invalid for the field.

        Returns:
        the range of valid values for the field, not null

      • doIsSupported

        boolean doIsSupported(TemporalAccessor temporal)
        Implementation of the logic to check if this field is supported by the accessor.

        This method is not intended to be called by application code directly. Applications should use TemporalAccessor.isSupported(TemporalField) on the date-time object passing this as the argument. 

           boolean supported = date.isSupported(field);

        Implementations should be written using the fields available in ChronoField.

        Parameters:
        temporal - the temporal object to query, not null
        Returns:
        true if the date-time can be queried for this field, false if not

        Implementation of the logic to get the range of valid values for this field.

      • doGet

        long doGet(TemporalAccessor temporal)
        Implementation of the logic to get the value of this field.

        This method is not intended to be called by application code directly. Applications should use TemporalAccessor.get(TemporalField) or TemporalAccessor.getLong(TemporalField) on the date-time object passing this as the argument. 

           long value = date.get(field);

      • doWith

        <R extends Temporal> R doWith(R temporal,
                            long newValue)
        Implementation of the logic to set the value of this field.

        This method is not intended to be called by application code directly. Applications should use Temporal.with(TemporalField, long) on the date-time object passing this as the argument. 

           updated = date.with(field, newValue);

        The new value of the field is expressed as a long integer. The result will be adjusted to set the value of the field.

        Implementations should be written using the fields available in ChronoField.

        Returns:

        Throws:
